South Pacific invasive alien species gap analysis in DNA barcode reference libraries

Introduction

The goal of this analysis is to find out if there are any gaps in sequence reference databases for species that are of interest to the PacMAN project.

This notebook makes use of the caspr package, which is a set of R functions created to support data analysis within the PacMAN project.

Region of interest

library(caspr)
library(sf)
library(dplyr)

library(leaflet)

leaflet() %>%
  addProviderTiles("CartoDB.Positron") %>%
  addPolygons(data = st_as_sfc(wkt_south_pacific, crs = 4326), color = "#ff9900")

Creating the species checklist

Lets first get the expert priority species lists, which are managed by the PacMAN team on GitHub, as well as a checklist for the South Pacific based on the OBIS database and the World Register of Introduced Marine Species (WRiMS). The checklists are merged to obtain a single checklist.

cl_expert <- expert_checklists(enhance = TRUE) %>%
  select(taxonID, scientificName, taxonRank, phylum, references, remarks)
cl_obis <- obis_checklist()

cl <- cl_obis %>%
  full_join(cl_expert) %>%
  filter(taxonRank == "Species")

This gives us a checklist with 1142 species from 21 phyla. Of these species, 196 are on the expert priority species lists.

library(ggplot2)

phylum_stats <- cl %>%
  group_by(phylum) %>%
  summarize(species = n()) %>%
  arrange(desc(species))

ggplot() +
  geom_histogram(data = phylum_stats, aes(x = reorder(phylum, -species), y = species), stat = "identity") +
  xlab("phylum") +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90, vjust = 0.5, hjust = 1))

Checking BOLD for sequences

Of the 1142 species in our checklist, 643 have a BOLD identifier in the WoRMS database, but in this first implementation we are querying BOLD by taxon name and not by identifier.

Lets get the number of sequences in BOLD by species and marker:

library(bold)
library(purrr)
library(progress)

if (file.exists("df_bold.rds")) {
  df_bold <- readRDS("df_bold.rds")
} else {
  bold_list <- sapply(cl$species, function(x) NULL)
  pb <- progress_estimated(nrow(cl))
  for (i in 1:length(cl$species)) {
    if (is.null(bold_list[[i]])) {
      taxon <- cl$species[i]
      bold_list[[i]] <- caspr::bold_statistics(taxon)  
    }
    pb$tick()$print()
  }
  df_bold <- bind_rows(bold_list, .id = "id")
  saveRDS(df_bold, "df_bold.rds")
}

This gives us a table with 42 distinct marker codes and 707 species.

marker_stats <- df_bold %>%
  group_by(markercode) %>%
  summarize(species = n(), sequences = sum(sequences))

ggplot() +
  geom_histogram(data = marker_stats, aes(x = reorder(markercode, -species), y = species), stat = "identity") +
  xlab("marker") +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90, vjust = 0.5, hjust = 1))

Lets take a look at the completeness by phylum. For this analysis Im verifying that for each taxon at least one of the following markers is present: COI, 18S, rbcL, matK 1.

selected_markers <- c("COI-5P", "18S", "rbcL", "rbcLa", "matK")

df_bold <- cl %>%
  left_join(df_bold, by = c("scientificName" = "id")) %>%
  mutate(has_barcode = markercode %in% selected_markers)

species_barcode_stats <- df_bold %>%
  group_by(phylum, species, records) %>%
  summarize(has_barcode = as.logical(max(has_barcode)))

phylum_barcode_stats <- species_barcode_stats %>%
  group_by(phylum, has_barcode) %>%
  summarize(species = n()) %>%
  arrange(desc(has_barcode))

ggplot() +
  geom_histogram(data = phylum_barcode_stats, aes(x = phylum, y = species, fill = has_barcode), stat = "identity") +
  scale_fill_grey(start = 0.7, end = 0.3) +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90, vjust = 0.5, hjust = 1))

Lets check which species without barcodes have the most occurrences in OBIS. This table gives the five most abundant species for each phylum:
